the new US @-@ Mexico @-@ Canada trade agreement will retain US President Donald Trump &apos;s ability to enforce a 25 % tariff threat on imported cars , while exempting essentially passenger cars , pickups , and car parts imported from Canada and Mexico from paying tariffs , according to the trade deal &apos;s subsidiary arrangement announced on Monday .
if Trump imposed a so @-@ called &quot; 232 &quot; tariff on cars for national security reasons , both Mexico and Canada would have a quota of 2.6 million tax @-@ exempt passenger cars exported to the US each year .
under the ancillary arrangement , pickups produced in both countries would be fully exempt from customs duties .
if Trump increases car tariffs , Mexico will receive a $ 108 billion annual tax @-@ exempt quota for car parts , and Canada will receive a $ 32.4 billion quota .
both quotas are well above the current levels of production in both countries and provide room for growth in both countries &apos; exports .
Washington , DC / Mexico ( Reuters ) - After days of debate , President Donald Trump &apos;s administration and Canada are making concrete efforts to resolve trade @-@ policy differences , raising hopes that the North American Free Trade Agreement ( NAFTA ) will remain a tripartite agreement , Mexico said Friday .
the lack of detail is enough to prompt the governments of Mexico and the United States to abruptly halt plans to publish the text of the bilateral trade agreement and give Canada more time to join .
Mexico &apos;s president @-@ designate , Andrés Manuel Lopez Obrador , told reporters in Mexico that the US government had made new counter @-@ proposals to the Canadian government and said he would continue to press for all three countries to participate in NAFTA .
Il de fonso Guajardo , Mexico &apos;s economy minister , said the submission of the text of the US @-@ Mexico trade agreement to Mexican and US legislation had been delayed because the Canadian and US governments were &quot; very serious &quot; about trying to reach an agreement .
&quot; in the next 48 hours , we will know whether we are going to reach a text of a tripartite agreement or have to publish it , &quot; Guahardo said .
Guahardo said his United States and Canadian counterparts &quot; specifically requested &quot; that the publication of the text be delayed .
a spokesman for the US Trade Representative &apos;s Office ( USTR ) did not comment on the text of the US @-@ Mexico trade agreement or on the US @-@ Canada consultations .
officials from the Office of the Prime Minister and the Office of the Foreign Minister of Canada did not respond to requests for comments on the counter @-@ proposal .
according to foreign media reports , in a conservation center on the outskirts of the South African capital Pretoria , it is hard to see anything unusual about the two young lions playing together , but they are rare .
&quot; this is the first time in history that a lion has been born in artificial insemination -- the first pair in the world , &quot; announced the University of Pretoria .
scientists at school are working on the reproductive system of the female African lion .
Ganswyte , director of the Institute of Mammal Research at the University of Pretoria , said the two lions , born on August 25 , were male and female , quite healthy and normal .
his team finally made the breakthrough after 18 months of intensive experimentation .
&quot; we collected sperm from a healthy lion , &quot; Ganswyte told the media .
the researchers then performed artificial insemination on the female lion when the hormone levels reached an appropriate level .
&quot; fortunately , it turned out to be a success , &quot; Ganswyte said .
he said the researchers &quot; made several attempts , but surprisingly did not put much effort into them . &quot;
he said the breakthroughs could be repeated and scientists hoped to use the technology to save endangered large cats .
according to the International Union for Conservation of Nature , lions have been extinct in 26 African countries , and the total number of surviving wild lions has fallen by 43 per cent over the past 20 years , leaving only about 20,000 .
the African lion is classified by the group as a vulnerable animal .
&quot; if we don &apos;t do something for the animals , they &apos;re going to be extinct , &quot; Gansworth said .
he said the new technology did not require lions to be kept in captivity , but simply injected sperm into fertile female lions , as was done in North America and Europe for captivity .
South Korea &apos;s exports fell by the most in more than two years in September , but analysts blamed the decline on fewer working days and said global demand for South Korean goods remained strong despite rising trade tensions between China and the United States .
indeed , South Korea &apos;s exports rose daily last month .
in addition , earlier initial figures showed double @-@ digit growth in exports in the first weeks of September , before the long holidays .
South Korea &apos;s exports fell the largest year @-@ on @-@ year in September since July 2016 , more than the 5.7 % decline predicted by 11 analysts surveyed by Reuters .
preliminary figures released on Monday showed exports of $ 50.6 billion in September , down from $ 51.2 billion in August .
South Korean exports to China grew 7.8 per cent in September , for the twenty @-@ third straight month , despite concerns that the growing US @-@ China trade dispute could hurt other export @-@ dependent neighbors .
South Korean exports to the United States fell 11.8 per cent as sales of petroleum products fell .
overseas sales of South Korean memory chips and petroleum products grew by 28.3 per cent and 13.5 per cent , respectively , despite concerns that the so @-@ called &quot; super @-@ cycle &quot; of chips might have peaked .
&quot; however , the impact of the trade conflict will be inevitable , as South Korea relies heavily on the US and Chinese markets for its exports . &quot;
imports fell 2.1 per cent to $ 40.8 billion , less than the 3.1 per cent growth forecast in the Reuters survey .
the initial value of the trade surplus in September was $ 9.7 billion , up from $ 6.9 billion in August .
the Ministry of Industry says global manufacturing will remain buoyant thanks to the U. S. and EU countries , which is a positive factor for South Korean exports .
the statement pointed out : " the increase in export prices caused by higher oil prices will also benefit exports in the second half of this year . "
&quot; but the continuation of the trade conflict between the United States and China , coupled with increased market volatility following the US interest rate hike , are all negative pressures on exports . &quot;
exports rose to an average of $ 2.6 billion per working day in September , compared with $ 2.1 billion in August .
South Korea &apos;s Mid @-@ Autumn Festival falls on September 24 @-@ 26 , leaving September with only 19.5 working days , four days less than the same period last year .
South Korea &apos;s exports grew 4.7 % in January @-@ September from a year earlier .
manufacturing activity in South Korea rebounded in September , according to the Nikkei / Markit Purchasing Managers &apos; Index , but was underpinned by domestic orders as orders from China and Japan fell , threatening to overshadow other export prospects .
DPRK media criticize us for not relaxing sanctions against DPRK
the DPRK 's " labor news " published a signed editorial article on 30 september criticizing the united states for not relaxing sanctions against the DPRK while seeking dialogue with the DPRK , calling this a " contradictory " practice .
the article says that us secretary of state Pompeo said on 4 april that " in order to realize the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula , the key lies in the implementation of sanctions against the DPRK , " stressing that the us position on continuing to implement the un sanctions resolution remains unchanged .
in Singapore 's DPRK - us joint statement , both sides pledged to establish new DPRK - us relations commensurate with the aspirations of the DPRK and us peoples for peace and prosperity .
it would undoubtedly be paradoxical for the United States to call for dialogue while intensifying the crackdown of sanctions .
the article says : if we want to establish new DPRK - us relations , build a permanently consolidated peace system on the Korean peninsula , and realize the complete denuclearization of the Korean peninsula , we should put the building of trust in the first place , start with what can be done , and resolve it one by one in stages .
the article also said that the united states should understand that the crackdown of sanctions will not work for the DPRK .
the article says that even the " northern dwensk , " which preceded the " kazan , " made the us military admire it .
