foreign media : the United States and Canada reach a framework agreement on the North American Free Trade Agreement .
&#91; abstract &#93; The agreement includes Canada opening its dairy market to the US and the US not imposing tariffs on Canadian @-@ made cars for the time being .
according to foreign media reports , a Canadian source disclosed on the night of september 30 local time that the united states and canada had reached a framework agreement on the north american free trade agreement .
it was revealed that the agreement includes canada opening its dairy market to the united states and that the united states will temporarily not impose tariffs on Canadian - made automobiles .
on 27 august , the united states and mexico announced that they had reached a preliminary agreement in principle on updating the north american free trade agreement , but the united states and canada were unable to reach an agreement before the 31 august deadline set by the united states to extend the talks until 30 september .
prior to that , a spokesman for Canadian foreign minister Freeland said that canada would only sign a favorable agreement , " focusing on the substance rather than the timetable , " and that we would continue consultations in the hope of reaching an agreement that conforms to canada 's national interests . "
more than 90 percent of Brazilian women voters say presidential candidates do not consider women &apos;s needs .
more than 90 per cent of Brazilian women do not believe that presidential candidates take women &apos;s needs into account , according to figures released recently by the National Geographic Institute of Brazil ( IBGE ) .
Brazil , which now has 107 million women , would be 13 th in the world , twice as large as Spain , if women from all over the country were brought together to form a nation , the report said .
in Brazil , women account for 52 per cent of the electorate and men for 48 per cent of the electorate , and although women account for a very high percentage of the electorate , they account for only 10 per cent of the Brazilian Congress .
of the 193 countries in the world , Brazil ranks only 154th in political participation , higher than the Arab countries .
after more than two decades of struggle for rights , Brazilian women have still not succeeded in obtaining their rights .
Natalia Mori , a Brazilian sociologist , points out that this phenomenon exists because of the combined effects of an ancient patriarchal society , racism , and capitalist values .
&quot; politics is supposed to be a society where citizens claim civil rights , identity , access to public goods , and multiple social groups form the same society ... But Brazilian politics belongs to the monopoly of one group , and the majority of the population is not represented . &quot;
a previous study by the Locomotiva Institute in Brazil also noted that 94 per cent of Brazilian women did not feel that elected politicians represented their rights , 90 per cent of Brazilian women disagreed with the decisions made by politicians and 93 per cent disagreed with the current government &apos;s governance policies .
&quot; we need to reverse the underrepresentation of women in parliament , and Brazil &apos;s political system is still affected by inequality ... So far , Brazil &apos;s politics still have serious gender , class and racial discrimination , &quot; said Natalia Mori .
despite women &apos;s lack of rights , most Brazilian women still believe in the power of democracy .
the survey showed that 76 per cent of women believed that they could make a difference in democratic elections and 72 per cent were interested in politics .
in addition , 55 per cent of women believe that democratic politics is the best way to reduce prejudice against women .
