a tripartite trade agreement between the united states and mexico will open up new opportunities for 500 million people .
according to foreign media reports , a joint statement by Canadian foreign minister Freeland and us trade representative Letterszeitzer , published on the Canadian government website , said that the united states , canada , and mexico had reached a tripartite trade agreement , which would be called the " us - mexico - canada three - nation agreement . "
Canada &apos;s CTV News earlier quoted senior US sources as saying Canada and the United States had overcome their differences and reached an agreement on the North American Free Trade Agreement ( NAFTA ) .
the washington post quoted two informed sources as saying that the agreement reached between the united states and canada on september 30 will retain the north american free trade agreement as a tripartite trade agreement , and the heads of state of the three countries will sign a new agreement within two months .
" today , canada , the united states and mexico have agreed on a new trade agreement - the us - mexico triangle agreement ( USMCA ) , which will provide our workers , farmers and companies with a high standard of trade agreements that will lead to freer markets , fairer trading and more sustainable economic growth , and that will strengthen the middle class , create high - paying jobs , and create new opportunities for about 500 million people , " the statement said .
it is learned that the current north american free trade agreement was signed by the united states , mexico and canada in 1994 .
after assuming office , Trump announced plans to revisit the agreement and sign it .
the three countries started the negotiation process in 2017 .
the election of Okinawa governor , which was held ahead of schedule because of the death of former governor Ong chang - hsiung , was announced in the early hours of 1 july local time . Danny , who opposed the planned relocation of the us military base in japan , was successfully elected .
the final results of the election , which was counted on september 30 , showed that Yucheng won a total of 3966.32 million votes , the highest number in the history of the Okinawa prefectural governor election , and more than 80,000 more votes than his main rival , Tsoi chun - soon .
a total of four candidates participated in the election , with a turnout of 63.24 per cent , 0.89 percentage points lower than in the 2014 Okinawa prefectural governor election .
Yucheng told the media on the 1 st that the results of the election show that the county people do not want to let the efforts of governor eng chang be wasted . he will carry forward the legacy of governor eng chang and continue to work with the Japanese government and the us government on opposing the us military base relocation plan and the closure of the uteng base .
Putian - based us military base in yono city , Okinawa county , has long been criticized . the Japanese and us governments previously agreed to relocate it to the frontier area of yono city , but the people of Okinawa strongly opposed the move , hoping to completely relocate the base from Okinawa .
with regard to the relocation plan strongly opposed by the county people and the demand to revoke the permission for land reclamation along the frontier and ancient coastal areas , Yucheng said that he did not take a confrontational and divisive stand with the central government at the beginning . he hoped that the two sides would fully exchange views and show their intention to resolve the issue through consultation .
Japanese prime minister Shinzo abe also told the media this morning that he would seriously accept this result and make efforts to revitalize Okinawa and lighten the burden on the base .
Japanese chief cabinet secretary Naoto Kan said at a news conference on the 1st that the government 's policy of relocating us military bases as soon as possible has not changed .
he also expressed his intention to hold talks with Yucheng .
Yucheng will officially assume office as governor of Okinawa prefecture on the 4th of this month .
since the mid @-@ 2000s , as China &apos;s demand for oilseeds has grown , Paul Thomas , a North Dakota farmer in the United States , has grown more and more soybeans in his field .
the shift peaked this year when he planted 1,600 acres of soybeans on 5,000 acres , an unprecedented scale .
but Thomas and many other farmers like him plan to transplant corn and wheat , the staple crops in US farming areas , by 2019 .
for the first time in 35 years , American farmers are growing more soybeans than maize this year .
the reason for planning to switch to other food crops is that American farmers face difficulties selling soybeans in the context of US President Donald Trump &apos;s trade war with China .
China usually buys about 60 per cent of US soybeans for export , but in recent months there has been almost no US soybean purchases due to the trade war , causing soybean prices to fall to a decade low .
Thomas plans to grow more wheat next year , hoping to make more by reducing his dependence on crops that depend on Chinese demand .
soybean prices &quot; hit us hard , &quot; says Thomas .
he said the spot price for soybeans near his farm was $ 7.10 per bushel without Chinese demand , while the price needed to cover the cost was $ 8.50 .
U.S. farmers are planting record amounts of soybeans this year , and the harvest is expected to hit record highs .
at a time when they were vulnerable to shocks , they were hit by a trade war .
in response to Trump &apos;s imposition of tariffs on imports of Chinese goods , China imposed import tariffs on imports of US soybeans in July .
the United States Department of Agriculture will release its first estimate of the area planted next year , expected to include consideration of the impact of tariffs .
the estimate is expected to confirm private sector expectations of a reduction in soybean soybean acreage .
according to a report Reuters saw , Informa Economics predicted on Oct. 19 that corn cultivation would increase by 4 % to 92.7 million acres ( 37.5 million hectares ) in 2019 , and soybean cultivation would fall by 7 % to 83 million acres .
Informa also predicts a 4 per cent increase in wheat cultivation in the United States .
soybeans planted before retaliatory tariffs rose to 89.6 million acres this year , about 15 million acres more than a decade ago .
the area under maize cultivation has increased by less than 5 million acres since 2008 to 89.1 million acres , and wheat cultivation this year stands at 47.8 million acres , the lowest level in 100 years .
Aron Carlson , president of the Illinois Maize Planting Association , whose total acreage is 3,600 acres , has spent nearly half of this year growing soybeans , but plans to cut it in the future .
he said he could increase maize cultivation by up to 20 per cent on his farm in northern Illinois , the largest soybean @-@ growing state in the United States .
soybeans produce less per acre per acre than maize , but require less fertilizer , making soybeans generally less costly to grow .
if farmers move to end @-@ value maize , it may raise costs , but it will benefit some businesses , including Andersons Inc . fertilizer sellers .
Andersons CEO Pat Bowe told Reuters he expected conversion to corn would benefit fertilizer use .
Bayer is also expected to benefit from farmers switching to maize .
