&quot; when they catch thieves , they discover that their eyes and looks are different from those of ordinary passengers , who , besides staring at their pockets and backpacks , prefer to drill into the crowd rather than run away from people .
police also told reporters that suspects often wait for their cars to have no purpose , like to wander around the station , find the target of the next pickpocketing before they will follow them .
&quot; it &apos;s all empirical , &quot; he said . &quot; we &apos;ve been wearing plain clothes for a long time , and we know it . &quot;
in addition , the civilian police also suggested that " it is the most convenient and easy way to steal things in an outer pocket . "
